Lemme preface this by saying that I carried hugeee expectations for Tartine. Like almost unsurmountable. I was so excited to eat here that I dragged the bf here early on a Sunday because we had lunch plans but I wanted to fit in a quick breakfast. We waited in line for about 20 minutes before it was time for us to order. We split a bowl of bread pudding, but felt it would be a shame to wait so long for only that, so we also got some morning buns and a chocolate croissant to go. After all that waiting and hype, I tried their famous bread pudding and it was...just okay. I think it would do better with a creme based sauce instead of the caramel sauce that it came with, and it would also be more delicious with almost any other fruit than what we had, which was apples I think (berries and/or peaches would've made it phenomenal). The texture is what I like in a bread pudding -- light and airy, which is often hard to find in most places -- but it wasn't as good as M. Henry's in Chicago. I ate my morning bun the following day and that was just okay too. It was good and all, but also super buttery and did not taste like it was worth the calories. Overall, Tartine may just not be my style. I like interesting desserts with some flair, while Tartine specializes in classics (hence their banana cream pie and lemon bars). While their classic offerings are solid, I still don't understand the hype.

So basically at the Napa bridal shower last weekend, all we talked about were food and running. And after 10 years of not having run a single mile, I've begun to take up running. This is how persuasive my friends are. Similarly, we decided to hit up all the places they talked about on our way back down from Napa. A bunch of us are from LA, so it's not like we knew when we would get another chance to go on a foodventure in SF. Though we had just finished brunch at the Girl and the Fig in Sonoma, we were determined to hunt down the famed bread pudding and morning roll from Tartine. We happened to hit jackpot when we realized that Bi-Rite was just a block down, so clearly, we ended up hitting both one right after the other. The line was long at Tartine, but thanks to Yelp, we were reassured that the line would be fast and we'd be ordering in no time. Yelp stayed true, but boy, I wish someone would have warned up about the snippy lady that helped us (again, with the snippy San Franciscan remarks but hey, you know it's true). She had short black hair and the only one without a smile on her face. Since it was our first time, we asked about the morning rolls and she brusquely told us those were sold out hours ago and made us feel like we were asking her to pull a unicorn out of her ass. Then, I asked about the bread pudding because we didn't have time to stay and eat so we wanted to make sure we could get it to-go and it'd still be as great as people claimed. She gave us the, yeah, are you guys idiots and have never taken a thing to-go before look, and then she disappeared. What? But I wasn't finished ordering! So basically, another, much more pleasant, lady came to finish my order and then I was off. What a strange experience. I could deal with the snippy servers, but what really made me want to return were the amazing lemon poppyseed almond pound cake and the delicious strawberry bread pudding. Oh, and of course, I didn't get a chance to try the morning buns so that was enough reason to return. The poppyseed almond pound cake was the best I've ever had. It was extremely moist without being overbearingly sweet. Usually cakes that are too moist are drenched in syrup or something, but this was pure heaven. I could eat this every day for the rest of my life. It was THAT good. This is the only time I've felt bad for people that are allergic to nuts. The bread pudding was also exquisite. Even the day after, it was still one of the best bread puddings I've ever had. I can only imagine what it's like to have it fresh and served the way it's supposed to be served. Because we're nosy and observant people, we noticed this lady in front of us buying just one thing: the gougere. She waited in this darn line just for this small round bread?! It must be good. So, we asked her about it and she told us it's a cheesy hollow bread with lots of thyme. All I needed to hear was cheesy and it was in our bag. The gougere does have a strong thyme flavor, but it pairs well with the gruyere cheese. It's not overwhelmingly cheesy, but it is a nice savory snack to indulge in. Lastly, I also got a slice of the coconut passion fruit bavarian cake, the most expensive ($5.50) but the least enjoyable. The passion fruit was way too sour, and the coconut shreds were too hard. It was a strange combination that I wish I had decided against. Overall, if you're going to open up a French bakery, you better learn a few tricks from Tartine; they've done it right.

Everything looks and smells incredible. The banana cream pie was out of this world!

Tartine is worth the wait (60 minutes to be exact!). The French Country loaf was crispy on the outside and soft and chewy on the inside. It was warm and delicious when we ripped into it. The butter added on is nice, but certainly not necessary. Great surprise. The pastries were as expected: delicious. The almond (frangipane) croissant was stellar, and the pain au chocolat did not disappoint. We also bought four tarts for my birthday, to be consumed three days later. Wow. We were amazed at how well they kept up considering the moisture in the tarts. The crusts were perfect in all four. I highly recommend the banana cream, Frangipane, lemon, and hazelnut chocolate. All were shared between four of us. We all felt fulfilled. My favorites if the four are the lemon and banana cream. Yum.

Every bite I took was as if it was my last, thoroughly enjoyed by my tingling tongue. I really enjoyed the Banana Creme Tart as well. The texture contrasts from the crust to the cream was a well balanced delight. Overall I would say that this was a successful experience at Tartine. I have heard their cinnamon buns are amazing which I would love to try next time.

    So basically at the Napa bridal shower last weekend, all we talked about were food and running. And after 10 years of not having run a single mile, I've begun to take up running. This is how persuasive my friends are. Similarly, we decided to hit up all the places they talked about on our way back down from Napa. A bunch of us are from LA, so it's not like we knew when we would get another chance to go on a foodventure in SF. Though we had just finished brunch at the Girl and the Fig in Sonoma, we were determined to hunt down the famed bread pudding and morning roll from Tartine. We happened to hit jackpot when we realized that Bi-Rite was just a block down, so clearly, we ended up hitting both one right after the other.

    The line was long at Tartine, but thanks to Yelp, we were reassured that the line would be fast and we'd be ordering in no time. Yelp stayed true, but boy, I wish someone would have warned up about the snippy lady that helped us (again, with the snippy San Franciscan remarks but hey, you know it's true). She had short black hair and the only one without a smile on her face. Since it was our first time, we asked about the morning rolls and she brusquely told us those were sold out hours ago and made us feel like we were asking her to pull a unicorn out of her ass. Then, I asked about the bread pudding because we didn't have time to stay and eat so we wanted to make sure we could get it to-go and it'd still be as great as people claimed. She gave us the, yeah, are you guys idiots and have never taken a thing to-go before look, and then she disappeared. What? But I wasn't finished ordering! So basically, another, much more pleasant, lady came to finish my order and then I was off. What a strange experience. I could deal with the snippy servers, but what really made me want to return were the amazing lemon poppyseed almond pound cake and the delicious strawberry bread pudding. Oh, and of course, I didn't get a chance to try the morning buns so that was enough reason to return.

    The poppyseed almond pound cake was the best I've ever had. It was extremely moist without being overbearingly sweet. Usually cakes that are too moist are drenched in syrup or something, but this was pure heaven. I could eat this every day for the rest of my life. It was THAT good. This is the only time I've felt bad for people that are allergic to nuts. The bread pudding was also exquisite. Even the day after, it was still one of the best bread puddings I've ever had. I can only imagine what it's like to have it fresh and served the way it's supposed to be served.

    Because we're nosy and observant people, we noticed this lady in front of us buying just one thing: the gougere. She waited in this darn line just for this small round bread?! It must be good. So, we asked her about it and she told us it's a cheesy hollow bread with lots of thyme. All I needed to hear was cheesy and it was in our bag. The gougere does have a strong thyme flavor, but it pairs well with the gruyere cheese. It's not overwhelmingly cheesy, but it is a nice savory snack to indulge in.

    Lastly, I also got a slice of the coconut passion fruit bavarian cake, the most expensive ($5.50) but the least enjoyable. The passion fruit was way too sour, and the coconut shreds were too hard. It was a strange combination that I wish I had decided against. Overall, if you're going to open up a French bakery, you better learn a few tricks from Tartine; they've done it right.

    This place definitely has excellent bread, but I'm not sure they're the only bakery around that can produce bread with this kind of moisture and flavor. If you live in Sonoma and Marin county, chances are you've stumbled upon amazing bread without having to wait 42 minutes.

    That being said, the theory and technique is impressive. I rarely care for bread but this bread is very good. Wait in line for 42 minutes good...probably not. It is just bread. But I had plenty of time to kill so I thought I would try it.

    Sandwiches are warm and a bit too rich, with no vegetable to cut through it. However, the flavors are very good.

    If it weren't for the crazy long line, perhaps my expectations wouldn't have been so high!
